From the descriptive statistic table, it seems that White targets (woman and man) have the mean score that are in between the scores of Asian and Black targets, so for the target race variable in lmer model, we are going to use White as a reference group and code as 0.

Core analysis

Children’s choices varied significantly by target gender β = 0.70, F(1, 1) = 51.06, p < .001, with children more likely to select women over men. There were also significant effects of target race. Children selected Asian targets more often than White targets β = 0.55, F(1, 1) = 64.72, p < .001, and White targets more often than Black targets β = –0.20, F(1, 1) = 8.38, p = .004.

There is significant two-way interaction between target gender and target race. Specifically, children’s choice on White or Black targets differ by the target gender (β = -0.64, F(1, 1) = 21.72, p < .001), Children’s choice on White vs. Asian targets also differ by target gender (β = -0.68, F(1, 1) = 24.06, p < .001).

There is significant two-way interaction between target gender and stereotype dimension such that children’s choice on woman vs. man target differ based on stereotype dimensions (i.e., smart or nice) (β = 0.85, F(1, 1) = 19.1, p < .001).

There is significant three-way interaction between target gender, target race, and stereotype dimension. Children’s choice of gender and White or Black targets differ by stereotype dimension (β = -0.82, F(1, 1) = 8.95, p < .001), children’s choice of gender and White or Asian targets also differ by stereotype dimension (β = -0.78, F(1, 1) = 8.09, p < .001).

Breaking down the effects to understand the interactions:

Target gender x whiteBlack interaction:
Interpretation: Participants’ choices do not significantly differ between white and Black choices when considering men (p = 0.21), but do significantly differ between white and Black choices when considering women (p < .001). Namely, participants are more likely to choose a white woman than a Black woman.
